<DOC><DOCNO> AP890407-0213 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 1915EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-07 0527</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0540</SECOND><HEAD>Snow In Georgia, Record Heat In Southern California</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   A heat wave continued Friday over the Southwest, withtemperatures rising past 100, but in the East snow fell at higherelevations of the southern Appalachians.   The mercury hit a record 100 degrees in downtown Los Angeles at1 p.m. Downtown had a record-tying 100 Tuesday and record highs of105 Wednesday and 106 Thursday.   Other early afternoon readings in southern California included108 in Palm Springs, 100 in Burbank, and 93 in San Diego. Anestimated 60,000 people crowded Santa Monica Beach, lifeguards said.   The National Weather Service predicted the beginning of acooling trend Saturday with the dissipation of the Santa Anaweather condition, which began with warm wind last weekend.   Snow fell at midday over the higher elevations of southern WestVirginia, western Virginia and western North Carolina.   Early in the day, up to 4 inches of snow fell in the mountainsof northeastern Georgia, and schools in three counties were closedbecause of slippery roads.   Rain fell across much of the rest of Virginia, West Virginia andNorth Carolina, and across eastern Tennessee, eastern SouthCarolina, the Georgia coast, and northeastern Florida.   The heaviest rainfall during the 6 hours up to 2 p.m. EDT was0.83 of an inch at Cape Hatteras, N.C.   Snow was scattered over western sections of Pennsylvania and NewYork state, and across northwestern Lower Michigan.   Snow also extended over northern and central North Dakota andnorthwestern Minnesota, changing to rain or rain mixed with snowacross southwestern North Dakota and the eastern half of SouthDakota. Rain reached from eastern Nebraska and western Iowa intonorthwestern Missouri.   In northeastern North Dakota, up to 3 inches of snow fell duringthe morning over Cavalier and Pembina counties. In adjacentnorthwestern Minnesota, 4 inches fell at Badger and Roseau and 6inches fell at Hallock.   Also along the North Dakota-Minnesota border, ice jams and rapidsnow melt continued to swell the Red River. It was forecast tocrest at Fargo, N.D., at almost 20 feet above flood stage duringthe weekend.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 24degrees at Warroad, Minn., to 109 at Palm Springs, Calif. Friday'slow for the Lower 48 states was 13 degrees at International Falls,Minn.   For Saturday, snow, some mixed with rain, was forecast overnorthern Maine, Upper Michigan, northern Lower Michigan andWisconsin. Morning snow changing to rain was forecast over Montanaand northern Wyoming. Rain was forecast from central Maine acrossinland sections of the Carolinas, northern Georgia, northernAlabama, northern Mississippi, the Tennessee Valley, the OhioValley and the remainder of the Great Lakes.   Highs in the 30s and 40s were predicted from New England and NewJersey across Montana and Wyoming; in the 50s and 60s from thecentral Atlantic Coast across the Ohio Valley, the TennesseeValley, Missouri, the central Plains, the central Rockies andWashington state; in the 90s from southwestern Texas across thesouthern half of California; near 110 over the desert Southwest;and generally in the 70s and 80s over the remainder of the nation.</TEXT></DOC>